---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
---

<DocsLayout
	title="Microsoft Teams (Workflows)"
	description="Send notifications to Microsoft Teams via Power Automate (Workflows) webhooks — the successor to the retiring Office 365 connectors."
	section="Services"
	prev={{ title: 'Microsoft Teams', href: '/docs/services/msteams' }}
	next={{ title: 'ntfy', href: '/docs/services/ntfy' }}
>
	<h1>Microsoft Teams (Workflows)</h1>
	<p>
		Send notifications to Teams channels via the <strong>Workflows</strong> app
		(powered by Power Automate). This is the successor to the
		<a href="/docs/services/msteams">Office 365 incoming connectors</a> that
		Microsoft is
		<a href="https://devblogs.microsoft.com/microsoft365dev/retirement-of-office-365-connectors-within-microsoft-teams/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">retiring</a>.
	</p>

	<h2>URL format</h2>
	<p>
		A Workflows webhook URL carries a cryptographic <code>sig</code> token that
		must be preserved exactly, so notifly stores the whole HTTPS URL by swapping
		its scheme from <code>https</code> to <code>workflows</code>:
	</p>
	<CodeBlock
		code="workflows://<host>/<path>/triggers/manual/paths/invoke?...&sig=..."
		lang="text"
		label="scheme"
	/>
	<p>
		The easiest way to produce this is
		<a href="/docs/builder/smart-paste">smart paste</a> — paste the raw HTTPS URL
		you copied from Teams and it converts automatically. You can also do it
		interactively in the <a href="/docs/builder/playground">URL Builder</a>.
		Registered under both <code>workflows://</code> and the
		<code>workflow://</code> alias.
	</p>

	<h2>Example</h2>
	<CodeBlock
		code={`import { notify } from '@ambersecurityinc/notifly';

await notify(
  {
    urls: [
      'workflows://default.b0.environment.api.powerplatform.com/powerautomate/automations/direct/workflows/WORKFLOW_ID/triggers/manual/paths/invoke?api-version=1&sp=%2Ftriggers%2Fmanual%2Frun&sv=1.0&sig=SIGNATURE',
    ],
  },
  { title: 'Release', body: 'v3.0 deployed successfully', type: 'success' }
);`}
		lang="typescript"
	/>

	<h2>Creating the webhook</h2>
	<ol>
		<li>Open the Teams channel you want to post to.</li>
		<li>Click <strong>…</strong> (More options) next to the channel name and select <strong>Workflows</strong>.</li>
		<li>
			Choose the <strong>"Post to a channel when a webhook request is received"</strong>
			template (also shown as <em>"Send webhook alerts to a channel"</em>).
		</li>
		<li>Configure the target team and channel, then <strong>Save</strong>.</li>
		<li>Copy the generated webhook URL — it looks like:
			<CodeBlock
				code={`https://<env>.environment.api.powerplatform.com/powerautomate/automations/direct/workflows/<id>/triggers/manual/paths/invoke?api-version=1&sp=...&sv=1.0&sig=...`}
				lang="text"
				label="workflows webhook url"
			/>
		</li>
	</ol>
	<p>
		Older flows issue Logic Apps style URLs
		(<code>https://&lt;host&gt;.logic.azure.com:443/workflows/.../triggers/manual/paths/invoke?...</code>) —
		both are supported.
	</p>

	<h2>Message format</h2>
	<p>
		Messages are posted as a simple <code>&#123; "text": "..." &#125;</code>
		payload, which the built-in template renders with basic Markdown. When a
		<code>title</code> is provided it becomes a bold first line, followed by the
		<code>body</code>.
	</p>

	<h2>Workflows vs. the legacy connector</h2>
	<ul>
		<li>
			New Teams webhooks should use <code>workflows://</code>. The legacy
			<a href="/docs/services/msteams"><code>msteams://</code></a> connector still
			works where it is already configured, but Microsoft is blocking creation of
			new connectors.
		</li>
		<li>
			Button rendering is not supported for message cards posted through
			Workflows.
		</li>
	</ul>
</DocsLayout>
